\cf0 The solution they devised was as elegant as it was revolutionary: the joint stock company. The Dutch East India Company, founded in 1602, allowed dozens or even hundreds of investors to pool their resources for these massive undertakings. But what made this truly transformative was not just the pooling of capital, but the fact that these ownership stakes could be bought and sold to others, creating the world's first modern stock exchange right there in Amsterdam. Suddenly, our farmer's simple IOU to society had evolved into something far more sophisticated - a transferable claim on future profits from ventures he might never see, in lands whose names he could not pronounce. This represented more than just a clever financial innovation. The fundamental relationship between humans and value creation had shifted. Wealth was no longer necessarily tied to the land you tilled or the services you personally provided. Capital itself - that accumulated surplus value from countless past labors - could now be deployed independently to generate even more value. The blacksmith's son could invest in a spice voyage without ever leaving his village, and the farmer could own a piece of ships sailing to Java while never seeing the ocean. This venture funding process would later be called Schumpeter\'92s Circular Flow and would be the engine of economic growth and increasing material prosperity of the world ever since. When some young genius from MIT has no money and a new idea for a technology, they must present themselves to venture capitalists (representing people with no ideas and lots of money) in order to vet his idea and potentially invest (give him money in exchange for ownership in the company). This is how the vast majority of new technologies are funded in modern society\
